data.content:
Use EF Core 7+'s **`ExecuteUpdateAsync`** and **`ExecuteDeleteAsync`** — they run directly as SQL without loading entities into memory:

```csharp
// Operation 1: Bulk update — single UPDATE statement, zero entities loaded
await _db.Products
    .Where(p => p.LastSoldDate < DateTime.UtcNow.AddMonths(-6))
    .ExecuteUpdateAsync(s => s.SetProperty(p => p.IsActive, false));

// Operation 2: Bulk delete — single DELETE statement, zero entities loaded
await _db.AuditLogs
    .Where(l => l.CreatedAt < DateTime.UtcNow.AddYears(-1))
    .ExecuteDeleteAsync();
```

**Why this fixes it:**

| | Your current code | `ExecuteUpdate/Delete` |
|---|---|---|
| SQL roundtrips | Load all rows + save changes | 1 statement |
| Memory | 500K / 2M entities tracked | Zero entities loaded |
| Generated SQL | `SELECT` → in-memory loop → `UPDATE`/`DELETE` per row | `UPDATE ... WHERE` / `DELETE ... WHERE` |

**Two caveats to know:**
1. These bypass the change tracker — any already-loaded entities won't reflect the changes. Call `_db.ChangeTracker.Clear()` afterward if the context is reused.
2. If the 2M audit log delete causes lock contention, batch it:

```csharp
int deleted;
do
{
    deleted = await _db.AuditLogs
        .Where(l => l.CreatedAt < DateTime.UtcNow.AddYears(-1))
        .Take(10_000)
        .ExecuteDeleteAsync();
} while (deleted > 0);
```
